title: TRAINING: ACLU-PA Transparency Project
description:
The Transparency Project is a nonpartisan initiative that monitors county-level government in order to defend and expand civil rights and liberties in Pennsylvania. The project, which began in 2022 as a way to find out about voting and election-related actions by county election boards, will expand in 2025 to monitor county commissioner and county council meetings for threats to civil rights and liberties. The project is run by the ACLU-PA with assistance from the League of Women Voters, Promote The Vote PA and other organizations and relies on volunteer observers to attend meetings, in person or virtually, and report back to ACLU-PA staff.

Please join us, along with Rebecca Cusumano-Seidel of the ACLU-PA and learn how YOU can get involved with this important work!

Volunteers do NOT need to be a county resident to participate!

title: Virtual Comment Party: Stop the Chesapeake Compressor Station!

sponsor.name: Chesapeake Climate Action Network / Action Fund

description:
Join us for a virtual comment party to speak out against the proposed hybrid gas-electric compressor station in Chesapeake, VA. This facility — planned near several environmental justice communities and a local middle school — would be tied to the Virginia Reliability Project and used to power AI paper production for Smurfit WestRock.

Compressor stations are industrial facilities that release toxic air pollutants while pushing gas through pipelines, thereby placing surrounding communities at risk of long-term health and environmental harm.

We need at least 25 public comments submitted to the Virginia State Corporation Commission (SCC) by May 23rd to trigger a formal hearing and your voice can help us reach that goal.

At this event, we’ll give you a brief overview of the project, walk you through the comment process, provide talking points, and answer any questions you have. Whether it’s your first time taking action or you’ve done this before, you’ll leave with a comment submitted and a sense of connection to others fighting for environmental justice in Virginia.

Let’s show decision-makers that our communities are watching and we demand better.

title: Pride, Poetry, & Plastics Workshop with Storytelling with Saris
description:
We're excited to join Storytelling with Saris for an early Pride Month workshop focused on the disproportionate impacts of climate change and sea level rise on the LGBTQ+ community. Join us for an evening of art, pride, poetry writing, plastics education, and a light dinner.  

Saris are a particularly sustainable garment, traditionally made of cotton or silk, and passed down from generation to generation within families. Unfortunately, many types of clothing today are now fast fashion and are made from plastic-based products and petrochemicals like polyester. These materials are derived from fossil fuels and are bad for our health and warm the climate. 

This workshop will empower each of us to use art as a form of advocacy as we write poetry and make art on the saris inspired by the courage and rich history of the LGBTQ+ community who are disproportionately impacted by climate change.

title: Rally to make the rich pay their fair share!

location.venue: Rhode Island State House (Front steps, Smith Street side)

description:
It's time for the top 1% of Rhode Islanders to pay their fair share in income taxes and do their part to make sure that Rhode Islanders don't lose any more hospitals, bus lines, homes, shelters, and schools.

Join RI Working Families Power, OpenDoors RI, and many more organizations as we rally in front of the State House to let our state legislators know that it is past time to enact legislation that would increase income taxes on Rhode Islanders making more than $625,000 per year.

The "Revenue for Rhode Island" legislation, sponsored by Rep. Karen Alzate and Sen. Melissa Murray, would generate $190 million in additional revenue that our state could use towards shielding us from federal austerity measures. Passing this legislation, and other taxes on the rich like the second homes tax and the tax on wealth, would be a massive step towards in ensuring that Rhode Islanders are able to not just survive, but thrive in the years to come. 

Join us as we loudly proclaim that enough is enough. Fund the working families of our state, not the 1%!

This event is co-sponsored by Revenue for Rhode Island (https://revenueforri.org/)

title: Public education should be bi-partisan: A Virtual Town Hall for GOP Public Education Allies
description:
**Protecting public education takes all of us working across party lines.**

Now more than ever, all voices are needed to advocate on behalf of public schools, educators, and students.  

**Join us for a conversation** about what is going on in Washington and how it affects working families, students, and rural communities back home.

**Hear from NEA President Becky Pringle, NEA’s Republican Caucus co-chairs, and fellow state and local affiliate leaders** as we reimagine ways to take collective action to fight for our students and the future of public education together.  

**We will discuss:**

- Current federal budget proposals and political landscape 

- Why conservatives should care about programs like Title I, IDEA, Medicaid, and school meals 

- Tactics to effectively engage GOP elected officials at all levels of government 

- Examples of where GOP educators and politicians are making a difference 

You'll leave with expert feedback and real strategies for maximizing your engagement with elected officials and defending public education in your community! 

_Please share questions, concerns, and ideas via this form._

_This is a moderated discussion, and we hope to get through as many questions as possible. Please submit your questions to the panelists in advance._

title: Third Act: Accountability Postcards
description:
Third Act is a national grassroots organization dedicated to organizing and mobilizing Americans age 60+ to safeguard our democracy and protect our climate. We know with your support, we can connect with voters, build voter enthusiasm, and help elect democracy and climate champions!

Third Act is partnering with Activate America in writing to Democratic and Democratic leaning voters in key Republican swing districts to let them know what their Republican representatives are up to! This information may not be getting through to voters via other media. Right now we are sharing info on votes to cut Medicaid while giving big tax breaks to billionaires and also talking about tariffs. We are also asking voters to call their representatives and ask them not to cut Medicaid or support tax breaks for billionaires while regular people lose services.

Note volunteers supply their own postcards and stamps for this effort. Please mail postcards as you complete them and by June 15 at the latest.

Follow the instructions below to sign up and then see the available postcard campaign choices and request voter addresses. 

If you have questions about Third Act's work, please contact "mike at third act dot org"


**You will receive addresses and a postcard script from our partner, Activate America. You can supply your own postcards and stamps, or download and print a custom Third Act Vote postcard (see below).**

***INSTRUCTIONS***

Sign up and then click on "Complete Your Registration Here." You will then be directed to a second form called "Postcards to Voters." Choose any campaign, and let us know how many names and addresses you want us to send to you. You will also receive a confirmation text.  

After you choose your campaign and request your voter addresses, you will get a Confirmation Email from Activate America. The link to the form "Postcards to Voters" is in the Confirmation Email. Use this link to order more names and addresses in the future.

**If you don't see the email, please check your Spam and Trash folders** for an email from  addresses@activate-postcards.vote or [staffname]@activateamerica.vote before reaching out to us.

- The deadlines for mailing postcards vary, and are stated on the script you will receive. You can also look for the deadlines on the same page as the order form.

- ***You supply your own postcards and stamps.***

- Click here:  https://thirdact.org/act/write-postcards-to-voters-main for info on downloading a print-at-home Third Act VOTE postcard, buying stamps, and/or buying other postcard designs.

Learn more about Third Act’s work (https://bit.ly/3N81XHn), including increasing participation in elections, advocacy to ensure voting access, voter education, cultural engagement, and direct action.

- For questions about receiving your voter addresses, contact anna@activateamerica.vote. 
- For questions about Third Act's Protect the Vote work, please contact info@thirdact.org.

***TAKE ACTION NOW!***

Thank you!

**The Team at Third Act**

title: Housing Speaks! Immigrant Housing Leadership Panel
description:
Housing Speaks! - Immigrant Housing Leadership Panel

Date: Thursday, May 15th, 2025

Time: 6:30-8:30 PM

Location: Bayanihan Community Center | 1010 Mission St, San Francisco, CA 94103

QUESTION SUBMISSION: https://forms.gle/mXfEh8fDFg9AEFRD8

Background: As recent federal policies attack immigration, language access, and affordable housing, immigrant families are experiencing a strong uncertainty in our city.

"Housing Speaks!" is a critical community panel event addressing the language access and housing rights for immigrant communities in San Francisco.

The Bill Sorro Housing Program (BiSHoP) is bringing together key leaders from immigrant-serving organizations to discuss immigration, language and housing access concerns with members of the San Francisco community.

Join us as we explore how community organizations are protecting their clients and what strategies can protect our most vulnerable neighbors, from direct services & case management, to tenant organizing and site preservation!

Format:
Panel discussion with community leaders (40-60 minutes)
Community Q&A (30-40 minutes)
Networking reception with food provided (30 minutes)

Who Should Attend:

- Anyone interested in immigration & housing rights
- Housing advocates, case managers, service providers, non-profit members
- San Francisco tenants, especially from SoMa, Mission, and TL neighborhoods
- Media/Journalists encouraged to attend!

Don't miss this moment to learn, meet, and join the movement to protect housing access for immigrant communities in San Francisco!

Questions? For more information, please contact our Community Manager  via donate@bishopsf.org.

About the Organizer

Bill Sorro Housing Program (BiSHoP) is a non-profit increasing and defending affordable housing access for diverse, multilingual, low-income families in San Francisco.

Founded in 2009, they provide support with affordable housing, rental subsidy, and tenants’ rights cases for 800+ families across The City from their office in SoMa - offered in English, Tagalog, Arabic, Spanish, and French.
